                "type": "guid",
                "guid": "242e3f96-382c-3e93-99fa-a415be189e75"

            {
                "type": "guid",
                "guid": "d1a9b001-1df7-fbd7-ae4c-6ca7065286ec"

        "keywords": [
            "Kansas City Chiefs",
            "Philadelphia Eagles",
            "NFL"
        ],
        "story": "NEW ORLEANS -- \u2014 <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4682618/cooper-dejean\">Cooper DeJean</a>, <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3693166/josh-sweat\">Josh Sweat</a> and the Philadelphia Eagles\u2019 ferocious defense denied <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3139477/patrick-mahomes\">Patrick Mahomes</a>, <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/15847/travis-kelce\">Travis Kelce</a> and the <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/team/_/name/kc/kansas-city-chiefs\">Kansas City Chiefs</a> a Super Bowl three-peat.\n\n\r\n              It wasn\u2019t even close.\n\n\r\n              <a href=\"https://x.com/NFL/status/1888750819786256472\">DeJean got a pick-6</a> on his <a href=\"https://apnews.com/article/super-bowl-birthday-cooper-dejean-barkley-697c91e35802293f29cf0aed95e15436\">22nd birthday</a>, Sweat tormented Mahomes and the Eagles routed the Chiefs 40-22 on Sunday to secure the franchise\u2019s second Super Bowl championship.\n\n\r\n              <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4040715/jalen-hurts\">Jalen Hurts</a> threw for two touchdowns and ran for a score on a tush push <a href=\"https://apnews.com/article/super-bowl-2025-mvp-hurts-ede8baa76799513871fcde1795b6d1ac\">to earn Super Bowl MVP honors</a>, and Vic Fangio's defense was so dominant that the Eagles didn't need much from <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3929630/saquon-barkley\">Saquon Barkley</a>.\n\n\r\n              The game-changing running back finished with 57 yards, <a href=\"https://apnews.com/article/super-bowl-eagles-barkley-5e28abc26e50169e124fa99c2ef4058e\">breaking Terrell Davis\u2019 record</a> for yards rushing in a season, playoffs included. Hurts threw for 221 yards.\n\n\r\n              \u201cThis is the ultimate team game. You can\u2019t be great without the greatness of others. Great performance by everybody \u2014 offense, defense, special teams,\u201d coach Nick Sirianni said. \u201cWe didn\u2019t really ever care what anyone thought about how we won, or their opinions. All we want to do is win.\u201d\n\n\r\n              With Donald Trump <a href=\"https://apnews.com/article/trump-nfl-super-bowl-first-president-766c628f4ea3faf38d100e4f33f2ac8c\">becoming the first president in office to attend a Super Bowl</a>, the Eagles outplayed Kansas City in every facet, delighting a raucous pro-Philly crowd that celebrated each score with a familiar rendition of \u201cFly! Eagles! Fly!\u201d\n\n\r\n              Even <a href=\"https://apnews.com/article/super-bowl-taylor-swift-travis-kelce-35c7b3b896c226566e4afa0baa7b69c5\">Taylor Swift\u2019s presence</a> couldn\u2019t help the Chiefs. They lost for the first time in 10 games this season with the pop superstar in a suite watching boyfriend Travis Kelce, who didn\u2019t catch a pass until late in the third quarter.\n\n\r\n              Not in Kansas City\u2019s worst nightmares could its fans have imagined such a lackluster performance. The Chiefs had won three of the previous five Super Bowls, losing 31-9 to Tom Brady and the <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/team/_/name/tb/tampa-bay-buccaneers\">Tampa Bay Buccaneers</a> four years ago.\n\n\r\n              Mahomes was 8-0 against Fangio\u2019s defenses before the longtime coordinator and former Broncos head coach outcoached Andy Reid, capping his first season with his hometown team. Reid fell to 3-3 in Super Bowls, including a loss with the Eagles.\n\n\r\n              The Eagles sacked Mahomes six times, the most of his career, including 2 1/2 by Sweat. And they did it without Fangio calling a single blitz.\n\n\r\n              \u201cDefense wins championships,\u201d Hurts said. \u201cWe saw how they played today. We saw the difference they made in the game. They gave us opportunities, gave us short fields. And we\u2019re able to do what we do.\u201d\n\n\r\n              Barkley, the 2024 AP NFL Offensive Player of the Year, only had 31 yards rushing in the first half when Philly built a 24-0 lead.\n\n\r\n              The Chiefs were aiming to become the third team in NFL history to win three straight championships and the first to three-peat in the Super Bowl era.\n\n\r\n              Hurts nearly led the Eagles to victory against the Chiefs two years ago in Arizona, but Mahomes led a comeback and <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3055899/harrison-butker\">Harrison Butker</a> kicked the game-winning field goal in the final minute for a 38-35 victory. Mahomes rallied Kansas City to an overtime victory over San Francisco last year for the Chiefs' second straight title.\n\n\r\n              \u201cThat\u2019s a great football team and we had to come out and play our best, and we did,\u201d Sirianni said.\n\n\r\n              This time, a revamped Philly defense featuring eight new starters from the 2022 team made sure Mahomes had no chance to pull off his magic.\n\n\r\n              \u201cToday was a rough day all around. Nothing went right. I didn\u2019t coach well. Proud of our guys for fighting. We will learn from this,\u201d Reid said. \u201cToo many turnovers, too many penalties. Against a good football team, can\u2019t do that.\u201d\n\n\r\n              Sirianni, <a href=\"https://apnews.com/article/eagles-analysis-sirianni-sideline-antics-125b677b3a4d8cca37d89ead27b5fe1e\">who mocked fans chanting \u201cFire Nick!\u201d</a> during a victory over Cleveland in October and was called a \u201cclown\u201d on national television, should finally silence critics by adding a championship ring to a resume that includes the fifth-best winning percentage in league history.\n\n\r\n              Sirianni was showered with Gatorade with nearly three minutes left in the game while backup QB <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4240703/kenny-pickett\">Kenny Pickett</a> took snaps in mop-up duty.\n\n\r\n              Barkley helped push Hurts into the end zone from the 1 to give Philadelphia a 7-0 lead in the first quarter.\n\n\r\n              Up 10-0 after Jake Elliott\u2019s 48-yard field goal, Sweat and <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4571162/jalyx-hunt\">Jalyx Hunt</a> sacked Mahomes on consecutive plays. Mahomes then rolled out and made an errant throw that was picked by DeJean, who returned it 38 yards for a 17-0 lead.\n\n\r\n              It was Mahomes\u2019 first pick-6 in 21 career playoff games and ended a streak of 297 straight passes without an interception.\n\n\r\n              \u201cWe didn\u2019t start how we wanted to. The turnovers hurt. I take all the blame for that,\u201d Mahomes said. \u201cI didn\u2019t play to my standard.\u201d\n\n\r\n              All-Pro linebacker <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3917657/zack-baun\">Zack Baun</a> picked Mahomes again late in the second quarter, and Hurts connected with <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4047646/aj-brown\">A.J. Brown</a> on a 12-yard TD pass for a 24-0 lead.\n\n\r\n              <a href=\"https://x.com/NFL/status/1888774848114983241\">Hurts threw a perfect 46-yard TD pass to <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4241478/devonta-smith\">DeVonta Smith</a></a> to make it 34-0 late in the third.\n\n\r\n              Mahomes fired a 24-yard TD pass to <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4683062/xavier-worthy\">Xavier Worthy</a> to avoid the shutout, but the 2-point conversion failed. He threw two late, mostly meaningless TD passes, one to <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/15795/deandre-hopkins\">DeAndre Hopkins</a> and another to Worthy.\n\n\r\n              After two weeks of discussions about questionable calls that led to public perception that officials favor the Chiefs \u2014 a theory NFL Commissioner Roger Goodell called \u201cridiculous\u201d \u2014 the first penalty of the game only fueled critics.\n\n\r\n              A 32-yard pass from Hurts to Brown to the Chiefs 18 on fourth-and-2 was negated by a penalty for offensive pass interference. Brady, now a Fox analyst, and officiating analyst Mike Pereira both disagreed with the call, although Brown shoved Trent McDuffie\u2019s facemask.\n\n\r\n              On the next possession, the Eagles benefited from an unnecessary roughness penalty on McDuffie against <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/3121023/dallas-goedert\">Dallas Goedert</a> following an incomplete pass on third-and-5.\n\n\r\n              Hurts then connected with <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/player/_/id/4361409/jahan-dotson\">Jahan Dotson</a> on a 27-yard pass to the 1 and scored on the next play.\n\n\r\n              Hurts\u2019 streak of 217 passes without a pick ended in the first half when he was intercepted deep in Kansas City territory, but the Chiefs didn\u2019t capitalize.\n\n\r\n              The <a href=\"http://www.espn.com/nfl/team/_/name/gb/green-bay-packers\">Green Bay Packers</a> are the only NFL team to win three championships in a row, doing it from 1929-31 and 1965-67.\n\n\r\n              The NBA\u2019s Los Angeles Lakers from 2000-02, led by Kobe Bryant and Shaquille O\u2019Neill, are the last team in the major American professional leagues to win three straight titles.\n\n\r\n              ------\n\n\r\n              AP NFL: <a href=\"https://apnews.com/hub/nfl\">https://apnews.com/hub/nfl</a>",
